Use mdy dates|date=August 2014
File:Thriller platinum record, Hard Rock Cafe Hollywood.JPG|thumb|Platinum record for Michael Jackson's ''Thriller (Michael Jackson album)|Thriller'' (1982), the best-selling album of all time
This is a list of the world's best-selling albums of recorded music. To appear on the list, the figure must have been published by a reliable source and the record sales|album must have sold at least 20 million copies. This list can contain any types of album, including studio albums, extended plays, greatest hits, compilation album|compilations, various artists, Soundtrack album|soundtracks and remix album|remixes. The figures given do not take into account the resale of used good|used albums.efn|name=year

All albums included on this list have their available claimed figures supported by at least 30% in certified copies. The percentage amount of certified sales needed increases the newer the album is, so albums released before 1975 are only expected to have their claimed figures <!--These must be international or worldwide, not just American sales figures.-->supported by at least 30% in certified copies. However, newer albums, such as ''21 (Adele album)|21'' and ''Come Away with Me'', are expected to have their claimed figures supported by at least 70% in certified copies. Certified copies are sourced from available online databases of local music industry associations. This is the reason why albums that would otherwise make the list, such as ''The Sound of Music (soundtrack)|The Sound of Music'', ''In-A-Gadda-Da-Vida (album)|In-A-Gadda-Da-Vida'', ''Parallel Lines'', ''Spirits Having Flown'', ''Private Dancer'', ''Janet (album)|Janet'', ''Believe (Cher album)|Believe'', ''Bolo Ta Ra Ra..'', ''Human Clay'', ''Laundry Service'' and ''Back to Black'', have not been included. <!--Please do not add any albums into this section whose claimed figures are lower than 20 million. Also, keep in mind that all claimed figures must be published by reliable sources. To promote high levels of fact checking and editorial control, this list should source sales figures to news organizations and highly regarded music industry related organizations such as MTV, VH1, Billboard (magazine)|Billboard and Rolling Stone.-->

As a result of the methodology that the American and Canadian certification-awarding bodies (the RIAA and Music Canada respectively) use, each disc in a multi-disc set is counted as one unit toward certification, leading to many double albums on the list—such as Pink Floyd's ''The Wall'' and the Beatles' ''The Beatles (album)|The Beatles''—being certified with a number double the number of copies sold there. Such albums have the certifications for the number of copies (not discs) shipped indicated. Conversely, the American certification level for double albums that fit onto one compact disc, such as the ''Saturday Night Fever (soundtrack)|Saturday Night Fever'' Soundtrack album|soundtrack reflect the actual number of copies sold. In 2016, RIAA included streaming in addition to track sales and album sales based on the concept of album-equivalent unit for certification purposes, and certification therefore no longer reflects shipment alone.<ref>cite web|url=https://www.riaa.com/riaa-debuts-album-award-streams/|title=RIAA Debuts Album Award with Streams|work=RIAA|date=1 February 2016</ref><ref>cite web|url=https://www.riaa.com/gold-platinum/about-awards/|title=Gold & Platinum|work=RIAA</ref> For example, in the update of the certification for ''Their Greatest Hits (1971–1975)'' by the Eagles (band)|Eagles in August 2018, the album was certified 38× Platinum (increasing from the previous 29× Platinum certification in 2006) based on the new criteria, making it then the album with the highest certification in the United States.<ref>cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/8470996/riaa-eagles-greatest-hits-certified-38x-platinum-passing-thriller|title=RIAA: Eagles' Greatest Hits Certified 38x Platinum, Passing 'Thriller'|date=August 20, 2018|author=Associated Press|work=Billboard</ref>

Michael Jackson's ''Thriller (Michael Jackson album)|Thriller'', estimated to have sold 66 million copies worldwide, is the best-selling album.<ref name="Guinness">cite web|title=Best-selling album|work=Guinness World Records|accessdate=June 29, 2017|url=http://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/world-records/70133-best-selling-album</ref> Although sales estimates for ''Thriller'' have been as high as 120&nbsp;million copies, these sales figures are unreliable.<ref name="The New Yorker January 4">cite web|url=http://www.newyorker.com/culture/culture-desk/did-thriller-really-sell-a-hundred-million-copies|title=Did Michael Jackson's ''Thriller'' Really Sell a Hundred Million Copies?|last=Wyman|first=Bill|publisher=The New Yorker|date=January 4, 2013|accessdate=May 26, 2013</ref> Jackson also currently has the highest number of albums on the list with five, while The Beatles, Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna and Celine Dion each have three.

Groupings are based on different sales benchmarks, the highest being for claims of at least 40 million copies, and the lowest being for claims of 20–29 million copies. Albums are listed in order of number of copies sold and thereafter by the artist's first name. Markets' order within the table is based on the number of compact discs sold in each market, largest market at the top and smallest at the bottom.<ref name="31. Global Sales of Recorded Music by Country in 2010 (page 24)">cite web|url=http://www.riaj.or.jp/e/issue/pdf/RIAJ2012E.pdf|publisher=RIAJ|title=31. Global Sales of Recorded Music by Country in 2010 (page 24)|year=2012|accessdate=April 28, 2012</ref>
